# Primary constructors

Use **C# 12 primary constructors** for classes whose constructor only **captures dependencies / values** to private state. Prefer `record` primary constructors for value-shaped types.

## Preferred — DI service

```csharp
public sealed class TrialSeatReservationService(
    ITrialSeatRepository repository,
    IClock clock,
    ILogger<TrialSeatReservationService> logger)
    : ITrialSeatReservationService
{
    public async Task<TrialSeatReservation> ReserveAsync(Guid tenantId, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        if (repository is null) throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(repository));
        if (clock is null)      throw new ArgumentNullException(nameof(clock));

        DateTime now = clock.UtcNow;
        return await repository.ReserveAsync(tenantId, now, ct);
    }
}
```

## Preferred — value type

```csharp
public sealed record AlertEnvelope(Guid AlertId, AlertSeverity Severity, DateTime RaisedAt);
```

## Avoid

```csharp
// Avoid: hand-written ctor that just assigns parameters to fields, when a primary ctor would do
public sealed class TrialSeatReservationService : ITrialSeatReservationService
{
    private readonly ITrialSeatRepository _repository;
    private readonly IClock _clock;
    private readonly ILogger<TrialSeatReservationService> _logger;

    public TrialSeatReservationService(
        ITrialSeatRepository repository,
        IClock clock,
        ILogger<TrialSeatReservationService> logger)
    {
        _repository = repository;
        _clock = clock;
        _logger = logger;
    }
}
```

## Scope and guardrails

- **Null checks stay explicit** — primary constructors do not throw on null. Validate in the first member that uses each parameter (or once in a `Validate` helper) using **`CSharp-Terse-01-GuardClausesSameLine.mdc`**.
- Use primary ctors when the captured parameters become **read-only state**; avoid them when you also need overload chaining or significant constructor logic.
- Each class still goes in **its own file** per the project rule.
- For DTOs / value-shaped types, prefer `record` primary ctors with `init` accessors — they compose well with **`CSharp-Terse-04-CollectionExpressions.mdc`** and **`CSharp-SimpleProperties-OneLine.mdc`**.
